TY  - JOUR
T1  - Some Unintended Consequences of Intention to Quit
AU  - Bowen, David E.
Y1  - 1982/04/01
PY  - 1982
DA  - 1982/04/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/amr.1982.4285563
DO  - 10.5465/amr.1982.4285563
T2  - Academy of Management Review
JF  - Academy of Management Review
JO  - AMR
SP  - 205
EP  - 211
VL  - 7
IS  - 2
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - With the use of a two-cycle model of job search, the situation of employees who intend to quit, but do not, is analyzed to see if intention to quit can be useful in explaining job behaviors other than quitting. Absenteeism and being fired are suggested as unintended consequences of intention to quit. The relationship between these unintended consequences and job performance also is examined. The analysis is guided by the theoretical premises of Mobley's models of the employee turnover process.
AB  - With the use of a two-cycle model of job search, the situation of employees who intend to quit, but do not, is analyzed to see if intention to quit can be useful in explaining job behaviors other than quitting. Absenteeism and being fired are suggested as unintended consequences of intention to quit. The relationship between these unintended consequences and job performance also is examined. The analysis is guided by the theoretical premises of Mobley's models of the employee turnover process.
